The issue here is where do yo want to convert the **List** to **Set**,
the conversion can be done before **Class3** mapped to **Class4** and after that.

So the struggle here is if you want to make **Set&lt;Class3&gt;** from **List** and then convert it to **Set&lt;Class4&gt;** or first apply conversion from **Class3** to **Class4**. This is important because List can contain duplicated values, where the Set contains only of unique values. Making `List&lt;Class3&gt;` to `Set&lt;Class3&gt;` as first operation will depend on the equality of Class3 objects. Making `List&lt;Class4&gt;` to `Set&lt;Class4&gt;` will check the equality implemented for Class4.

The little mapper between objects is always required, if you don&#39;t want to explicitly declare mapping method use a copy constructor `Class4(Class3) {...}` for example.

Here&#39;s an example:
```
import lombok.*;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Set;
import java.util.function.Function;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class MappingWithLambdas {
    private static Function&lt;Class1,Class2&gt; c1To2WithMapping = c1 -&gt; {
        Function&lt;Class3,Class4&gt; c3to4 = c3 -&gt; {
            Class4 c4 = new Class4();
            c4.setX(c3.getX());
            c4.setY(c3.getY());
            return c4;
        };
        Function&lt;List&lt;Class3&gt;, Set&lt;Class4&gt;&gt; listToSet = l -&gt; l.stream().map(c3to4).collect(Collectors.toSet());
        Class2 c2 = new Class2();
        c2.setX(c1.getX());
        c2.setY(c1.getY());
        c2.setDatas(listToSet.apply(c1.getDatas()));
        return c2;
    };
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Class1 c1 = new Class1();
        c1.setX(&quot;X&quot;); c1.setY(&quot;Y&quot;);
        c1.setDatas(List.of(new Class3(&quot;x&quot;, &quot;y&quot;), new Class3(&quot;x&quot;, &quot;y&quot;), new Class3(&quot;x&quot;, &quot;y&quot;)));
        System.out.println(c1);
        System.out.println(&quot;Using mapping function: &quot;);
        System.out.println(c1To2WithMapping.apply(c1));
        Function&lt;Class1,Class2&gt; c1to2WithNew = Class2::new;
        System.out.println(&quot;Using Class2 constructor: &quot;);
        System.out.println(c1to2WithNew.apply(c1));
        System.out.println(&quot;Simply with constructor: &quot;);
        System.out.println(new Class2(c1));
    }
}
@Data
class Class1 {
    private String x;
    private String y;
    private List&lt;Class3&gt; datas;
}
@Data
class Class2 {
    private String x;
    private String y;
    private Set&lt;Class4&gt; datas;
    private Function&lt;List&lt;Class3&gt;, Set&lt;Class4&gt;&gt; listToSetWithNew = l -&gt; l.stream().map(Class4::new).collect(Collectors.toSet());
    Class2() {}
    Class2(Class1 c) {
        this.x = c.getX();
        this.y = c.getY();
        this.datas = listToSetWithNew.apply(c.getDatas());
//List&lt;Class3&gt;-&gt;List&lt;Class4&gt;-&gt;Set&lt;Class4&gt;
//        this.datas = c.getDatas().stream().map(Class4::new).collect(Collectors.toSet());
//List&lt;Class3&gt;-&gt;Set&lt;Class3&gt;-&gt;Set&lt;Class4&gt;
//        this.datas = new HashSet&lt;&gt;(c.getDatas()).stream().map(Class4::new).collect(Collectors.toSet());
    }
}
@Data
class Class3 {
    private String x;
    private String y;
    Class3(String x, String y) {
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
    }
}
@Data
class Class4 {
    private String x;
    private String y;
    Class4() {}
    Class4(Class3 c) {
        this.x = c.getX();
        this.y = c.getY();
    }
}
```

`@Data` annotation comes from Lombok library, which created the setters, getters and toString for me.

And the output of this should look similar to this:
